{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":"2026-04-25T21:37:19.719Z","tool_name":"write_file","tool_id":"write_file_1777153039719_0","parameters":{"content":"# Verification Report — T-008@20260425T183959Zb\n\n**Verify Agent:** gemini-3-flash-preview\n**Date:** 2026-04-25\n**Artifacts Reviewed:**\n- `my-claw/tools/sample_capture_daemon.py`\n- `tests/test_sample_capture_daemon.py`\n- `sdp/logs/Verify_T-008_20260425T183959Zb_1777152936.log`\n\n## Correctness\nThe implementation of the heuristic acoustic feature analyzer matches the requirements for task T-008Zb.\n- `AcousticFeatures` dataclass correctly captures the requested numeric features: spectral centroid, bandwidth, and transient density.\n- `analyze_acoustic_features` implementation correctly uses `_spectral_magnitude` (reusing existing RFFT+Hanning logic) and `_count_transients` (reusing existing energy-deviation logic).\n- Spectral centroid calculation follows the standard first-moment formula.\n- Spectral bandwidth calculation follows the standard second-central-moment (spread) formula.\n- Transient density is correctly normalized to transients per second.\n- Edge cases for empty or silent input are handled correctly (returning 0.0 for features).\n\n## Completeness\nThe task work for sub-slice Zb is fully complete:\n- The raw numeric feature extractor is implemented and exposed via `AcousticFeatures` and `analyze_acoustic_features`.\n- Comprehensive unit tests cover functional correctness across different input types (tone, noise, transients, silence).\n- As requested, it reuses existing audio utilities from the `sample_capture_daemon.py` tool.\n\n## Consistency\nThe implementation is consistent with the `T-008Za` work (SampleTags schema) and other analysis primitives in `sample_capture_daemon.py`. It follows the established pattern of using `dataclasses` for structured data and `numpy` for signal processing.\n\n## Security\nNo security vulnerabilities or unsafe practices identified. The logic is purely computational and operates on local memory buffers.\n\n## Quality\nThe code is high quality and idiomatic:\n- Reuse of primitives (`_spectral_magnitude`, `_count_transients`) avoids logic duplication.\n- Frozen dataclass ensures immutability.\n- Tests use `pytest.approx` and clear fixture-based data generation.\n- Documentation for new functions is clear and concise.\n\n## Issues Found\n- [ ] No blocking or minor issues found in the implemented features.\n- [ ] **Note on Hardening:** The candidate hardening items regarding `bootstrap_identity()` on startup were considered out of scope for this specific feature implementation, consistent with precedent in `ESCALATIONS.md` for other utility/analysis tasks in this project. The `sample_capture_daemon.py` currently focuses on local audio capture and does not yet participate in the federation/identity subsystem.\n\n## Verdict: PASS\n\n## Notes for Lead Agent\nThe acoustic feature analyzer is solid and well-tested. It provides exactly the numeric foundation needed for the subsequent \"warm\", \"metallic\", etc. tagging logic. The reuse of the existing transient detector ensures that \"percussive\" tags will be consistent with the \"interesting-moment\" triggers.\n","file_path":"sdp/verification/t-008@20260425t183959zb-verify.md"}}
